# apache-pulsar Best Practices

This document outlines essential best practices for developing applications with Apache Pulsar, ensuring that your code is efficient, maintainable, and reliable.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use a Consistent Package Structure
Organize your code into a clear package structure to enhance readability and maintainability. Group related classes together.

❌ BAD
```plaintext
src/main/java/com/example/
- Producer.java
- Consumer.java
- Utils.java
- SomeOtherClass.java
```

✅ GOOD
```plaintext
src/main/java/com/example/pulsar/
- producer/
  - MyProducer.java
- consumer/
  - MyConsumer.java
- utils/
  - PulsarUtils.java
```

### Keep Classes Focused
Each class should have a single responsibility. This makes it easier to test and maintain.

❌ BAD
```java
public class PulsarService {
    public void produceMessage() { /*...*/ }
    public void consumeMessage() { /*...*/ }
    public void logMetrics() { /*...*/ }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```java
public class MessageProducer {
    public void produceMessage() { /*...*/ }
}

public class MessageConsumer {
    public void consumeMessage() { /*...*/ }
}

public class MetricsLogger {
    public void logMetrics() { /*...*/ }
}
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use CompletableFuture for Asynchronous Operations
Always prefer `CompletableFuture` for async tasks to keep your code non-blocking.

❌ BAD
```java
ListenableFuture<String> future = someAsyncMethod();
future.addListener(() -> { /*...*/ }, executor);
```

✅ GOOD
```java
CompletableFuture<String> future = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
    return someAsyncMethod();
}, executor);
future.thenAccept(result -> { /*...*/ });
```

### Implement Thread-Safety
Ensure all public classes are thread-safe. Use `@NotThreadSafe` annotation for classes that are not.

❌ BAD
```java
public class MessageQueue {
    private List<String> messages = new ArrayList<>();
    public void addMessage(String message) {
        messages.add(message);
    }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```java
import javax.annotation.concurrent.ThreadSafe;

@ThreadSafe
public class MessageQueue {
    private final List<String> messages = Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<>());
    public void addMessage(String message) {
        messages.add(message);
    }
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Use the Schema Registry
Always utilize Pulsar's Schema Registry for type-safe messaging. This avoids serialization issues and improves performance.

❌ BAD
```java
Producer<String> producer = client.newProducer(Schema.STRING)
    .topic("my-topic")
    .create();
```

✅ GOOD
```java
Producer<MyMessage> producer = client.newProducer(Schema.AVRO(MyMessage.class))
    .topic("my-topic")
    .create();
```

### Optimize Message Size
Keep your messages small to reduce latency. If you need to send large payloads, consider breaking them into smaller messages.

❌ BAD
```java
producer.send(largeMessage);
```

✅ GOOD
```java
for (String part : splitMessage(largeMessage)) {
    producer.send(part);
}
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Reflection in Tests
Never use reflection in your unit tests. Instead, use package-private visibility or `@VisibleForTesting` to expose necessary methods.

❌ BAD
```java
Method method = MyClass.class.getDeclaredMethod("privateMethod");
method.setAccessible(true);
```

✅ GOOD
```java
class MyClass {
    void packagePrivateMethod() { /*...*/ }
}

// In your test
MyClass myClass = new MyClass();
myClass.packagePrivateMethod();
```

### Ensure Backward Compatibility
When implementing new features, ensure backward compatibility in your wire protocols to avoid breaking existing consumers.

❌ BAD
```java
// Changing the message structure without versioning
```

✅ GOOD
```java
// Use versioning in your message schema
```

## Testing Approaches

### Write Unit Tests for All Changes
Every change in your codebase must be accompanied by unit tests to maintain code quality.

❌ BAD
```java
// No tests for new feature
```

✅ GOOD
```java
@Test
public void testMessageProduction() {
    MessageProducer producer = new MessageProducer();
    producer.produceMessage();
    // Assertions
}
```

### Use Structured Logging
Adopt SLF4j with structured (JSON) logging for better observability and easier debugging.

❌ BAD
```java
logger.info("Message produced: " + message);
```

✅ GOOD
```java
logger.info("Message produced", Markers.append("message", message));
```

By following these best practices, you will ensure that your Apache Pulsar applications are robust, maintainable, and efficient. Always keep learning and adapting to new features and improvements in the Pulsar ecosystem.